    {
      "id": "5a5da57a82109fd81fd3e225b986df9e6ee3dfc3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 278,
        "name": "Nathaniel Clark",
        "email": "nclark@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "utopiabound"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-05 18:25:09.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nThis doesn't seem like the right approach.  There should be a lu_nodemap level mutex to protect access to nm_member_hash",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "63a852032d58fa2fa78adc08e277d8ec507fae68",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 269,
        "name": "Kit Westneat",
        "email": "kit.westneat@gmail.com",
        "username": "kitwestneat"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-05 18:40:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThanks for the review. The situation that the lock tries to protect against is if two different nodemaps are reclassifying simultaneously. Say an export in nodemap1 needs to move to nodemap2. However, the export can't be added to nodemap2's hash while nodemap2 is reclassifying, because iterating the hash locks the hash, so nodemap1's reclassify blocks. If nodemap2 then finds a member export that needs to move to nodemap1, it will then try to add it to nodemap1's hash, block, and deadlock.\n\nSo the lock is there to try to prevent that situation, but I wasn't sure the best way to prevent it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
