    {
      "id": "a66a4e5397b41b6858a48f3f299b41ca7aced091",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-07 18:39:18.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "f37c33cdf64edea9ce791c778d22d130b13ab705",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 269,
        "name": "Kit Westneat",
        "email": "kit.westneat@gmail.com",
        "username": "kitwestneat"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-07 21:15:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJohn: Ok cool, I'll rewrite it to be more descriptive.\n\nNathaniel: I have some concerns about scaling when just using a big nodemap lock. Because the nodemaps are accessed on every MDT operation, it seems like there could be a major performance hit if we lock it during a reclassification when there are many clients that need to be iterated through. On the other hand, reclassifications shouldn't happen that often -- only when a new set of clients joins the filesystem, or an old set leaves. Perhaps it could be acceptable to pause IO for the amount of time it takes to reclassify the nodes if it only happen a handful of times a year. What are your thoughts? There's a project concall on Tuesdays, I'll bring it up there as well.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c69faa39c0ebd88efd39ce103c908caf39626298",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 278,
        "name": "Nathaniel Clark",
        "email": "nclark@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "utopiabound"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-24 19:02:05.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nMaybe a read/write mutex where most of the time all the readers just flow through.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "5e888ae4ffca29040152ff2ac72698243977eb3d",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2014-11-25 21:25:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nNathaniel, I see the reclassification lock as analogous to a cross-directory rename operation in the filesystem.  The kernel still only has a single global lock to avoid problems with parent/child renames, and nodemap reclassification is probably going to happen a LOT less than rename.\n\nAFAIK, nodemap reclassification (i.e. moving client(s) from one nodemap to another) is the only operation that will affect more than one nodemap at a time.  All of the others (client connect, disconnect/evict, lookup) will only affect a single nodemap, so adding serialization to those high-traffic operations may impact \"normal usage\" performance.  The current solution only impacts \"extremely rare usage\" performance (serializing two concurrent reclassifications) so I think it is a reasonable fix.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
